ISSUE 1 — Phase 10 Step 2: NPM SSL certificate never gets issued
Severity: High

The guide instructs the user to configure the proxy host but does not
explicitly state that the Details tab, SSL tab, and Advanced tab must
all be completed before the first Save. In practice, most users will
fill in the Details tab and save, then reopen to add SSL — which causes
NPM to silently reset the SSL tab to defaults (no certificate, Force SSL
off, HTTP/2 off). The user ends up with a working proxy but no TLS,
with no error message to indicate anything went wrong.

Recommended fix: Add a clear warning before the proxy host instructions
stating that all three tabs must be configured in a single save
operation. Example wording:

  "WARNING: Do not click Save until you have configured the Details,
  SSL, and Advanced tabs in the same session. If you save before
  visiting the SSL tab, NPM resets it to defaults on the next edit.
  You must complete all three tabs and click Save once."


ISSUE 2 — Phase 10 Step 2: HSTS not mentioned
Severity: Low

The guide covers Force SSL and HTTP/2 but does not mention HSTS
(Strict-Transport-Security). HSTS is a meaningful security improvement
that takes one toggle to enable and is a natural companion to Force SSL.
It should be mentioned with a brief explanation and the caveat that it
must only be enabled after the certificate is confirmed working.

Recommended addition: After the SSL tab instructions, add a note:

  "Once you have confirmed HTTPS is working, edit the proxy host again
  and enable HSTS in the SSL tab. Leave 'Also apply to subdomains' and
  'HSTS Preload' off unless you have a specific reason to use them."


ISSUE 3 — systemd-remount-fs.service fails on every boot
Severity: Low (cosmetic / confusing)

On current Bazzite builds using composefs, systemd-remount-fs.service
fails at boot with "overlay: No changes allowed in reconfigure." This
is a known upstream systemd/composefs compatibility issue and has no
effect on system operation. However it shows as a failed unit in
systemctl --failed and causes confusion.

Recommended addition: A note in Phase 1 Step 3 or Appendix A:

  "On current Bazzite builds, systemd-remount-fs.service may show as
  failed on every boot. This is a known harmless issue caused by
  composefs preventing remount of the immutable root. Mask it to keep
  a clean system state:

    sudo systemctl mask systemd-remount-fs.service
    sudo systemctl reset-failed"


ISSUE 4 — No mention of fail2ban sudoers rule and /etc/udev/rules.d/99-server-health.rules for non-root monitoring
Severity: Low

fail2ban-client requires sudo to query jail status. Any monitoring
script or dashboard run as a regular user will prompt for a password
every time. A targeted passwordless sudoers rule is the correct fix
and fits naturally alongside the other sudoers work in Phase 4 or 8.

Recommended addition:

  "To allow fail2ban status queries without a password prompt:

    echo "$USER ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/fail2ban-client" \
      | sudo tee /etc/sudoers.d/fail2ban-health
    sudo chmod 440 /etc/sudoers.d/fail2ban-health
    sudo visudo -c -f /etc/sudoers.d/fail2ban-health"

Also cpu and ram memory read need an udev rule like this one:

# Allow reading Intel RAPL (CPU Power) energy counters
SUBSYSTEM=="powercap", ACTION=="add", RUN+="/bin/chmod -R 444 /sys/class/powercap/intel-rapl:0/"

# Allow reading GPU usage/freq if restricted
SUBSYSTEM=="drm", ACTION=="add", RUN+="/bin/chmod -R 444 /sys/class/drm/card*/device/"

